                  subsections: [
                  {
                  subTitle: '',
                  content: `<em><span style="font-weight:900;color:#FF000A;font-size:larger"> Narada said:  </span></em>
                  <ol><li>When the Goddess Durga vanished and the Gods returned to their abodes, what happend next?</li>
                  <li>O dear, how did Mena and the Lord of the mountains perform the great penance? How did he beget a daughter of Mena. Please narrate.</li>
                  <br/><em><span style="font-weight:900;color:white;text-shadow: 1px 1px 2px grey;background-color:silver;font-size:x-large"font-size:larger">Shree Brahma said:  </span> </em>
                  <li>O best of Brahmins, O most excellent of my sons, listen to the great account. After bowing to Shiva with devotion, I shall narrate that story which increases devotion.</li>
                  <li>When Visnu and other Gods returned after instructing him, the Lord of the mountains and Mena performed a great penance.</li>
                  <li>Meditating on Siva and Shiva day and night with devout mind, the couple worshipped them continuously.</li>
                  <li>The beloved of the mountain wosrhipped the Goddess along with Shiva joyously. She gave charitable gifts always to the Brahmins for their satisfaction.</li>
                  <li>Desirous of obtaining a child, she worshipped Siva everyday for twenty seven years begining it in the month of March-April.</li>
                  <li>Observing a fast on the eight day of the lunar fortnight, she made charitable gifts of sweets, offerings of oblation rice cakes, puddings and fragrant flowers on the ninth day</li>
                  <li>She made a clay idol of the Goddess and worshipped her by offering various things on the banks of the Ganga in Ausadhiprastha<noteref1_note1footer>(1) - (10)</note></li>
                  <li>On some days, she observed a complete fast. On some days she observed sacred rites. Some days, wind alone constituted her food and some days she took only water.</li>
                  <li>With her mind fixed on Siva, Mena passed twenty seven years with pleasure and brilliant lustre.</li>
                  <li>At the end of twenty seven years, Uma the beloved of Shiva, the Mother of the World and identical with the universe became highly delighted.</li>
                  <li>The Goddess Siva, delighted by her good devotion, appeared in front of Mena in order to bless her.</li>
                  <li>Appearing to her in the form of divine limbs through a lustrous zone, she smilingly said to Mena</li>
                  <em><span style="font-weight:900;color:crimson;text-shadow: 3px 3px 2px pink;background-color:orange;font-size:x-large">The Goddess said:  </span></em>
                  <li>O Beloved of the mountain, I am highly delighted by your penance. O chaste lady, tell me what is the desire in your mind.</li>
                  <li>O Mena, whatever is desired by you by penance, sacred rites and ecstatic contemplation, I shall grant you and that too whenever you wish for it.</li>
                  <li>Then seeing the Goddess in her presence Mena bowed and said the following words:-</li>
                  <li><em><span style="font-weight:900;color:maroon;font-size:larger"> Mena said:  </span></em> O Goddess, your form has been perceived by me directly, just now. I wish to eulogize you. Be 
                  pleased</li>
                  <br/><em><span style="font-weight:900;color:white;text-shadow: 1px 1px 2px grey;background-color:silver;font-size:x-large"font-size:larger">Shree Brahma said:  </span> </em>
                  <li>On being thus requested by Mena the Goddess Uma the enchantress of everyone embraced Mena and was highly delighted</li>
                  <li>Acquiring very great wisdom, Mena eulogized Siva who had appeared in person by means of pleasing words with great devotion.</li>
                  <em><span style="font-weight:900;color:maroon;font-size:larger"> Mena said:  </span></em>
                  <li>I bow to the great Goddess<noteref2_note2footer>(2) - (11)</note>, the bestower of all desires, I bow to her who wields great illusion, the creator and sustainer of the Universe.</li>
                  <li>I bow to her of contemplative sleep, and to her, the wielder of great illusion and the cause of permament bliss. I bow to the mother of the Universe. I bow to Siddha having the garland of auspicious lotuses.</li>
                  <li>I bow to the grandmother of perpetual bliss. I bow to the Goddess who dispels the sorrow of the devotees, who is a model for all women and who constitutes the intellect of all living beings.</li>
                  <li>You are the cause of snapping of all fetters of ascetics. Which one of your powers can be sung by women like me?
                  You are violence mentioned in the Atharvaveda. You (of such powerful means) fulfil my desire</li>
                  <li>The living beings are being united to the different principles of the nature of permanence and otherwise and those
                  without substance are discarded. You are the inherent power of those permanent principles. In the proper time you
                  become a Woman of ability with Yogic powers.</li>
                  <li>You are the origin and the sustainer of the worlds. You are the eternal Prakriti, the great, by whom even the Brahman
                  is brought under control. O You of noble nature, O mother be pleased with me</li>
                  <li>YOu are the great power latent in fire; You are the burning power of the Sun's rays. YOu are the pleasing power
                  of extensive moonlight. O Goddess I bow to you</li>
                  <li>To good women you manifest yourself as their beloved; to persons of perfect self-control and sublimation, you manifest
                  yourself as eternal; to the entire Universe you manifest as desire; as of Visnu, you are the Maya, so 
                  you are of Siva.</li>
                  <li>You assume different forms as you please for the purpose of creation, sustenance and annhilation and give
                  birth to the bodies of Brahma, Visnu and Shiva. You of such potentiality, be please. Obeisance to you again.</li>
                  <em><span style="font-weight:900;color:white;text-shadow: 1px 1px 2px grey;background-color:silver;font-size:x-large"font-size:larger">Shree Brahma said:  </span> </em>
                  <li>Thus eulogized, the Goddess spoke to Mena desiring her to choose a boon.</li>    
                  <em><span style="font-weight:900;color:crimson;text-shadow: 3px 3px 2px pink;background-color:orange;font-size:x-large">Uma said:  </span></em>
                  <li>O Himacala's beloved you are as favorite to me as my vital air. Whatever you desire, I shall give you. There is nothing that I can
                  withhold from you</li>    
                  <li>ON hearing these nectar like words of the Goddess, the delighted Mena, the wife of Himacala said.</li>    
                  <em><span style="font-weight:900;color:maroon;font-size:larger"> Mena said:  </span></em>
                  <li>O Siva, Hail Hail! O Goddess if you consider me worthy of a boon, I shall chose one.</li>    
                  <li>O Mother of the Universe, at first, let me have a hundred sons endowed with longevity, heroism, prosperity and accomplishments</li>    
                  <li>After that, let me have a daughter of comely features and good qualities who will delight both the families and who will be revered by the three worlds.</li>    
                  <li>O Siva, be my daughter for fulfilling the needs of the Gods. O Goddess, be Rudra's wife and indulge in divine sports with the Lord.</li>    
                  <li><em><span style="font-weight:900;color:white;text-shadow: 1px 1px 2px grey;background-color:silver;font-size:x-large"font-size:larger">Shree Brahma said:  </span> </em>
                   On hearing the words of Mena, the delighted Goddess spoke smilingly, fulfilling her desire.</li>    
                   <em><span style="font-weight:900;color:crimson;text-shadow: 3px 3px 2px pink;background-color:orange;font-size:x-large">The Goddess said:  </span></em>
                  <li>May hundred heroic sons be born to you. One of them very strong will be born at first.</li>
                  <li>I shall be born as your daughter, since I am delighted with your devotion. Since I have been served by the Gods, I shall fulfil their desires and carry out their activities.</li>
                  <li><em><span style="font-weight:900;color:white;text-shadow: 1px 1px 2px grey;background-color:silver;font-size:x-large"font-size:larger">Shree Brahma said:  </span> </em>
                  <li>Sayig so, the Goddess Siva vanished from there even as Mena was watching.</li>
                  <li>O Dear one, on getting the desired boon from the Goddess, Mena attained immeasurable joy. Her misery accorded by penance vanished.</li>
                  <li>Bowing down in that direction, the chaste lady of delighted mind returned to her abode repeating the benedictory word 'Jaya' (be victorious)</li>
                  <li>She told her husband about the boon, which had already been understood by him though good omens, by her words which were rendered useless.</li>
                  <li>On hearing the words of Mena, the Lord of the Mountains became delighted. He praised his wife who was devoted to Shiva lovingly</li>
                  <li>O sage, when their mutual sexual intercourse took place, Mena conceived and the child in her womb gradually grew up.</li>
                  <li>She gave birth to a beautiful son Mainaka<noteref3_note3footer>(3) - (12)</note> who later on became the worthy recipient of the love of Naga ladies and who later on entered into
                  an alliance with the Lord of the ocean. O celestial sage, when Indra, the slayer of Vrtra became angry and began to chop off the wings of the mountains, Meinaka retained his wings, nay, he did not even
                  feel the pain of being wounded by the thunderbolt. He had good limbs. He had neat strength and prowess. He was the most important mountains born of him. He too became the Lord of Mountains. </li>
                  <li>In the city of Himacala, there was a wonderful celebration of the event. The coupl was highly delighted Their pain was at an end.</li>
                  <li>He gace monetary gifts and charitable offerings to Brahmins. The Devotion to Shiva and Siva increased </li>
                  </ol> 
                  <a href=\'#top\'><strong>Back To Top</strong></a></p>`,
                  notes: [`10. The Capital of Himavat. The name indicates that it was a market place for mountainous herbs`,
                  `11. The Goddess Siva is mentioned under a variety of names, forms, attributes and actions. She is contemplated on by the ascetics for the deliverance from the bondage of this world. She is propitated
                   for the satiation of desires with bloody sacrifices performed according to Atharvanic rites. <br/> She is represented in her milder and fiercer forms. In the milder, she is pleasing as the moon, gracious as the mother In the 
                   fiercer, she is furious as the fire and scorching as the Sun`,
                   `12. Mainaka, the son of Menaka and Himacala is represented as the most valiant of hundred sons of his parents. When Lord Indra clipped the wings of all mountains, Mainaka is said to have been the 
                   only one who escaped`
                  ]
                  }
                  ]
